# Security groups vs. NACLs

## Security group — at the ENI

- **Stateful** — reply auto-allowed
- **Allow-only** — no deny
- **Multiple per ENI**, combine **additively**
- Rules can **reference another SG** (tracks scaling)

## NACL — at the subnet (inverted)

- **Stateless** — reply **not** auto-allowed
- **Allow *and* deny**
- **Ordered**, first match wins
- Default NACL = allow all; custom = deny all

## The stateless trap

Responses use an **ephemeral port** (1024–65535). Allow inbound 443 but forget **outbound ephemeral** → handshake completes, then hangs.

**Rule:** SGs do 99%; use a NACL only to **deny** an IP at the subnet edge.
